Q1 : Where does ArrayList store data internally and why?
Ans : ArrayList internally stores elements in an Object[] array. It uses an object array because in Java every class
      is a child of Object, so this allows ArrayList to store any type of object.
      If interviewer asks for example
      Example:
      In an employee management system, initially we may store name and age, later we may need address, salary, or
      department. Since different types of data may be stored, ArrayList uses Object[] internally to store any object.

Q2 : Why do we need to override toString() method?
Ans : If we do not override the toString() method, then when we use System.out.println(object), Java will call the
      default toString() method of the Object class, which prints the reference value (ClassName + hashcode) of the
      object. But if we override the toString() method, then whatever logic we write inside it to display the object
      data will be executed. So when we use System.out.println(l), it will print the actual data present inside the
      array or object instead of the reference value.

      If we are using our own custom class(ex : Custom_ArrayList), then we usually need to override the toString()
      method so that when we print the object using System.out.println(object), it prints the actual data of the object
      instead of the reference value. But if we use predefined classes like ArrayList, LinkedList, HashMap, etc., we do
      not need to override toString() because these classes have already overridden the toString() method internally,
      so they automatically print the actual data stored inside them.

Q3: On transaction what will you prefer — ArrayList or Vector?
Ans : If the choice is only between ArrayList and Vector, I would choose Vector because it is synchronized and
      thread-safe, which helps when multiple transactions occur at the same time. However, in real-world systems,
      developers usually prefer ArrayList and handle concurrency using utilities like Collections.synchronizedList() or
      CopyOnWriteArrayList. In addition, database transactions (ACID properties) are used to maintain data consistency
      and correct balance.